## Example {.scrollable}

**Solve:**

$$y''-4y=\delta(t-2)t,\qquad y(0)=0,\quad y'(0)=1$$

**Solution:**

:::{.fragment}


$$\Rightarrow$$

$$s^2Y-1-4Y=2e^{-2s}$$

$$Y=\frac{2e^{-2s}+1}{s^2-4}$$
$$Y(s)=\frac{2e^{-2s}}{s^2-2^2}+\frac{1}{s^2-2^2}$$

Applying the inverse:

$$y(t)=\mathscr{L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{2e^{-2s}}{s^2-2^2}\right\}+\frac{1}{2}\sinh 2t$$
For the first term we can use: 

$$\boxed{\mathscr{L}\{u(t-a)f(t-a)\}=e^{-as}\mathscr{L}\{f(t)\}}$$
Then by inspection I identify $a=2$, and $f(t)=\sinh 2t\rightarrow f(t-a)= \sinh (2(t-2))$

Finally:

$$\boxed{y(t)=u(t-2)\sinh(2(t-2))+\frac{1}{2}\sinh 2t}$$


